## Phase 1 — Cost-of-Operations Benchmark Suite  (6 days)

> The measurement instrument reused by every later project. **Tooling: Google Benchmark** for the harness —
> but be able to explain `DoNotOptimize`/`ClobberMemory` (= `asm volatile` + memory clobber) under the hood.

### SP 1 — Harness + DCE barriers + measurement rigor  ⏱ 3 d
- [~] 🔴 CMake + Google Benchmark building & linking in Release (Docker/Linux) — **done**
- [~] 🔴 `DoNotOptimize` / `ClobberMemory` verified via asm that the loop is NOT elided/hoisted — **done**
      (found + fixed a real loop-invariant-hoisting bug, confirmed `mul` executes per-iteration in the asm)
- [~] 🔴 Core pinning (`pthread_setaffinity_np`) — **done**; `performance` governor — **deliberately deferred**
      to real bare-metal hardware (blocked in Docker/VM: no host-level sysfs write access without
      `--privileged`, and even then it's the VM's governor, not the physical host's)
- [~] 🔴 Percentiles p50 / p99 / p99.9 / p99.99 — **done** via manual raw-sample collection (`steady_clock`
      per-iteration + `std::sort` + index lookup), not GB's `ComputeStatistics` (which only computes stats
      over per-repetition means, not raw per-op samples — verified this distinction matters via a worked
      example before building)
- [ ] 🟡 `rdtsc` with serializing fences + TSC calibration vs `steady_clock` — **deferred**: x86-only, current
      dev environment is `aarch64` (Apple Silicon Docker); forcing `--platform=linux/amd64` would only give
      emulated x86 (Rosetta/QEMU), which produces scientifically meaningless nanosecond-scale timing data.
      Revisit on real x86 hardware.
- **Output:** a `bench` binary that prints a p50/p99/p99.9/p99.99 percentile table for a trivial op,
  runnable via one Docker command, with core pinning set (governor deferred, see above).

### SP 2 — Hardware cost report  ⏱ 3 d
- [~] 🔴 Memory-hierarchy latency: pointer-chase (dependent-load) benchmark — **mechanism done**. Built a
      closed random-cycle pointer chase (defeats prefetcher), swept working set via `SIZE` (= distinct cache
      lines touched, NOT `ARRAY_SIZE`), verified clean monotonic step: ~1.75ns (6KB, L1) → ~5.6ns (64KB, L1
      boundary) → ~27.7ns (640KB, L2, incl. TLB-miss overhead). No L3 on Apple Silicon (only L1+L2 exposed).
      **Remaining:** confirm the DRAM step (SIZE~1M, ARRAY_SIZE~16M), and only P50 is trustworthy in the
      Docker VM (tail = scheduling noise) — full L1→L2→L3→DRAM curve + real numbers come from the bare-metal
      x86 re-run (see Phase 6 / SP 11).
- [~] 🔴 Cache-line effects (stride) — **done w/ caveat.** Finding: constant-stride is prefetched, so
      stride-1 and stride-16 both run ~1-2ns/access even over 400MB DRAM — prefetcher hides the line penalty.
      Randomizing stride defeats it (~13-17ns) but conflates line-use with miss latency + in-loop RNG noise.
      Net: naive stride can't isolate the 64B-line cost on modern HW; false sharing shows it cleanly instead.
- [~] 🔴 False sharing — **mechanism done, effect unobservable in VM.** Two pinned threads increment adjacent
      vs `alignas(64)`-padded atomics; shared (16B) and padded (128B) came out identical (~36ms) because the
      2-vCPU virtualized box can't guarantee two *real* parallel physical cores (hypervisor co-schedules /
      time-slices → no cross-core coherency traffic → no ping-pong). Code is correct; hardware can't show it.
      ⏳ **REVISIT ON BARE METAL (SP 11):** re-run padded vs non-padded once on real dedicated cores (no core
      flipping / vCPU sharing) — expect padded to be several-x faster; that's the number for the report.
- [x] 🔴 Branch misprediction — **done, works on VM** (single-threaded/CPU-local). ~50/50 threshold; unsorted
      (unpredictable) ~17x slower than sorted (predictable). Kept a real branch (not `csel`) by putting the
      `DoNotOptimize` barrier *inside* the `if` body (volatile side effect can't be branchless-selected).
- [ ] 🟡 Virtual-call vs direct-call overhead
- **Output:** consolidated report (markdown + graphs). ⏳ **DEFERRED until after the bare-metal re-run (SP 11):**
  cache-line, false-sharing, and the real memory-hierarchy/governor numbers only exist on bare metal, so the
  report is assembled once, from trustworthy numbers, then — not from VM placeholders.

